{
  "query": "When planting non-crop vegetation to enhance natural pest control, what is the comparative evidence for planting new hedges versus plants that attract natural enemies with chemicals?",
  "relevant_summary": "For plants that produce chemicals that attract natural enemies, four studies from China, Germany, India and Kenya found evidence of effectiveness (Action 724). Three studies (including one replicated, randomised, controlled trial) found higher numbers of natural enemies in plots with plants that produce attractive chemicals, and all four studies found a decrease in either pest population or pest damage. One replicated, randomised, controlled study found an increase in crop yield. The crops studied were lettuce, orange, safflower and sorghum (Action 724).\n\nFor planting new hedges, the evidence is more mixed (Action 752). One randomised, replicated, controlled study from China found no effect on spiders in crops. Studies from France and China found mixed results, with one finding more natural enemies in hedges than adjacent crops while another found effects varied between crop types, hedge species and years. Two randomised, replicated, controlled studies from France and Kenya found natural enemy abundance in hedges was affected by the type of hedge shrub/tree planted. One study from Kenya found effects on nematodes varied between groups. The crops studied were barley, beans, maize and wheat (Action 752).\n\nAdditional evidence for hedgerows shows that one study from the USA found higher parasitization of pest eggs in tomato fields with hedgerows compared to fields with weedy edges, but only up to 100m into the crop, though pest damage to tomatoes was no different between hedgerow and weedy edge fields (Action 1401). Studies also found more natural enemies in fields with hedgerows compared to fields with weedy edges in some comparisons (Actions 1401, 2314).\n\nThe evidence suggests that plants producing chemicals that attract natural enemies show more consistent positive effects across studies, while hedge effectiveness varies significantly depending on hedge species, crop type, and other factors.",
