{
  "query": "To provide refuge for natural enemies, what is the comparative evidence for creating beetle banks versus leaving part of a crop unharvested?",
  "relevant_summary": "Based on the available evidence, both beetle banks and leaving part of crops unharvested provide refuge for natural enemies, but with different characteristics and effectiveness patterns.\n\nFor beetle banks, action 729 found that four studies and a review showed more invertebrate predators on beetle banks than in surrounding crops, though effects varied with time in one study. Eight studies compared numbers of predatory invertebrates on beetle banks with other refuge habitats - two studies found more natural enemies on beetle banks (with one showing only seasonal effects), one review found similar or higher numbers of predators, and four studies found similar or lower numbers compared to other habitats. Action 729 also noted that six studies examined effects on predator numbers in adjacent crops, with a review finding that predators increased in adjacent crops, though one study found no effect and two studies found small or slow movements of predators from banks to crops. Action 651 reported that five reports from replicated studies found positive effects on invertebrate densities and higher ground beetle density and species diversity, while five other replicated studies found lower or no difference in invertebrate densities on beetle banks relative to other habitats.\n\nFor leaving crops unharvested, action 725 found that three studies (including one replicated, controlled trial) showed an increase in abundance of predatory insects or spiders in the crop field or pasture that was partly uncut, while four studies (including three replicated, controlled trials) found more predators in the unharvested or unmown area itself. Two studies found that the ratio of predators to pests was higher in partially cut plots and one study found the same result in the uncut area. One replicated, controlled study found an increase in predation and parasitism rates of pest eggs in unharvested strips.\n\nThe evidence shows mixed results for pest control effectiveness: action 729 found that beetle banks could make economic savings if they prevented pests from reaching spray thresholds, while action 725 found variable effects on pest numbers with some studies showing decreases and others showing increases in pest numbers in partially cut plots.",
