{
  "query": "What are the overall effects of weed management strategies that rely on plant competition or chemical properties?",
  "relevant_summary": "Plant competition and chemical-based weed management strategies show mixed but generally positive effects across multiple studies. For plant competition strategies, growing plants that compete with damaging weeds resulted in reduced weed plant weight or ground cover in all nine studies from Australia, Slovakia, the UK and the USA, although two studies found this effect only in some years or conditions (action 722). Additionally, five studies found that competition reduced weed reproduction, survival or both, with one study showing an effect only in one year (action 722). Mixed pasture systems showed effectiveness with two studies from the USA finding reduced weeds in mixed compared to monoculture pasture (action 721). Push-pull cropping systems demonstrated pest control benefits, with two studies finding fewer witchweeds and two of three studies finding fewer pests overall (action 753).\n\nFor chemical-based approaches using allelopathic plant remains, results were variable. Six studies from Asia, Europe and North America found three studies showing reduction in weed growth and three showing effects that varied between years, weed groups, or control methods when comparing amended soils with weeded controls (action 728). When comparing with unweeded controls, two of four studies found reduced weed growth, but one found that residues applied too far in advance had reverse effects (action 728). However, the weed control effects were temporary, with two studies finding the decrease in weeds did not last beyond a few days or weeks after residue incorporation (action 728). These chemical approaches also affected crop growth, with two of three studies finding crop growth was inhibited by allelopathic plant remains, though this could be minimized by changing application timing (action 728).",
